> For now I'm focusing on API design (instead of implementation) and I'm not convinced that the current design, where `RawMenuAnchor` has 3 variations is the way to go.
> 
> My proposal is:
> 
> * Separate `.node` out as an individual widget
> * Make `RawMenuAnchor.overlayBuilder` the primary, or even the only, constructor.
> * Make the current default constructor delegate to `.overlayBuilder`.

Separating out the .node class makes sense to me. The only reason it's kept is to make it less confusing (all RawMenuAnchors can be found in the same class), but if that's more confusing then we can separate it out.

My push back to 2 and 3:

Say you want to make a menu, but something about the Material menu isn't adequate. Maybe you want to customize animations, or the backdrop, or you want to use a CustomScrollView rather than a SingleChildScrollView to enable sliver usage in your menu panel.

Example:

https://github.com/user-attachments/assets/7b48a7f6-87b0-4f44-96f4-c88e82ed44e7

The RawMenuAnchor default constructor allows you to achieve this with only a few lines of code:
<details><summary>With default constructor</summary>

```dart
RawMenuAnchor(
  controller: controller,
  panel: ConstrainedBox(
    constraints: const BoxConstraints(maxWidth: 120, maxHeight: 200),
    child: Material(
      borderRadius: BorderRadius.circular(8),
      clipBehavior: Clip.antiAlias,
      elevation: 8,
      color: Colors.white,
      child: CustomScrollView(
        slivers: <Widget>[
          for (int i = 0; i < 10; i++)
            SliverMainAxisGroup(
              slivers: <Widget>[
                PinnedHeaderSliver(
                  child: Container(
                    padding: const EdgeInsets.all(8),
                    decoration: BoxDecoration(
                      color: Colors.grey[100],
                      border: Border(
                        bottom: BorderSide(
                          color: Colors.grey[300]!,
                        ),
                      ),
                    ),
                    child: Text(
                      'Header $i',
                      style: Theme.of(context).textTheme.labelSmall,
                    ),
                  ),
                ),
                SliverList(
                  delegate: SliverChildListDelegate(
                    <Widget>[
                      for (int j = 0; j < 10; j++)
                        MenuItemButton(
                          onPressed: () => _handlePressed('Item ${i * 10 + j}'),
                          child: Text('Item ${i * 10 + j}'),
                        ),
                    ],
                  ),
                ),
              ],
            ),
        ],
      ),
    ),
  ),
  builder: (
    BuildContext context,
    MenuController controller,
    Widget? child,
  ) {
    return TextButton(
      onPressed: () {
        if (controller.isOpen) {
          controller.close();
        } else {
          controller.open();
        }
      },
      child: const Text('Edit'),
    );
  },
);
```

</details>

Users don't have to worry about accessibility, positioning, or any implementation details that go into building a menu fit for production. In all of my own projects, I use this constructor.

To achieve the same thing without the default constructor would look more like this:
(Note - I actually left out focus management because it was getting to be too long)

<details><summary>With overlayBuilder</summary>

```dart
  RawMenuAnchor.overlayBuilder(
  controller: controller,
  builder: (
    BuildContext context,
    MenuController controller,
    Widget? child,
  ) {
    return TextButton(
      onPressed: () {
        if (controller.isOpen) {
          controller.close();
        } else {
          controller.open();
        }
      },
      child: const Text('Edit'),
    );
  },
  overlayBuilder: (BuildContext context, RawMenuAnchorOverlayPosition position) {
    final MenuController menuController = MenuController.maybeOf(context)!;
    final Widget panel = Semantics.fromProperties(
      explicitChildNodes: true,
      properties: const SemanticsProperties(
        scopesRoute: true,
        label: 'Menu overlay',
      ),
      child: TapRegion(
        groupId: position.tapRegionGroupId,
        consumeOutsideTaps: true,
        onTapOutside: (PointerDownEvent event) {
          menuController.close();
        },
        child: FocusScope(
          skipTraversal: true,
          descendantsAreFocusable: true,
          child: Actions(
            actions: const <Type, Action<Intent>>{
              // Focus management
            },
            child: Shortcuts(
              shortcuts: const <ShortcutActivator, Intent>{
                SingleActivator(LogicalKeyboardKey.gameButtonA): ActivateIntent(),
                SingleActivator(LogicalKeyboardKey.escape): DismissIntent(),
                SingleActivator(LogicalKeyboardKey.arrowDown):
                    DirectionalFocusIntent(TraversalDirection.down),
                SingleActivator(LogicalKeyboardKey.arrowUp):
                    DirectionalFocusIntent(TraversalDirection.up),
                SingleActivator(LogicalKeyboardKey.arrowLeft):
                    DirectionalFocusIntent(TraversalDirection.left),
                SingleActivator(LogicalKeyboardKey.arrowRight):
                    DirectionalFocusIntent(TraversalDirection.right),
              },
              child: ConstrainedBox(
                constraints: const BoxConstraints(maxWidth: 120, maxHeight: 200),
                child: Material(
                  borderRadius: BorderRadius.circular(8),
                  clipBehavior: Clip.antiAlias,
                  elevation: 8,
                  color: Colors.white,
                  child: CustomScrollView(
                    slivers: <Widget>[
                      for (int i = 0; i < 10; i++)
                        SliverMainAxisGroup(
                          slivers: <Widget>[
                            PinnedHeaderSliver(
                              child: Container(
                                padding: const EdgeInsets.all(8),
                                decoration: BoxDecoration(
                                  color: Colors.grey[100],
                                  border: Border(
                                    bottom: BorderSide(
                                      color: Colors.grey[300]!,
                                    ),
                                  ),
                                ),
                                child: Text(
                                  'Header $i',
                                  style: Theme.of(context).textTheme.labelSmall,
                                ),
                              ),
                            ),
                            SliverList(
                              delegate: SliverChildListDelegate(
                                <Widget>[
                                  for (int j = 0; j < 10; j++)
                                    MenuItemButton(
                                      onPressed: () =>
                                          _handlePressed('Item ${i * 10 + j}'),
                                      child: Text('Item ${i * 10 + j}'),
                                    ),
                                ],
                              ),
                            ),
                          ],
                        ),
                    ],
                  ),
                ),
              ),
            ),
          ),
        ),
      ),
    );

    return ConstrainedBox(
      constraints: BoxConstraints.loose(position.overlaySize),
      child: Builder(
        builder: (BuildContext context) {
          final MediaQueryData mediaQuery = MediaQuery.of(context);
          final TextDirection textDirection = Directionality.of(context);
          return CustomSingleChildLayout(
            delegate: _MenuLayout(
              screenPadding: mediaQuery.padding,
              padding: EdgeInsets.zero,
              avoidBounds: DisplayFeatureSubScreen.avoidBounds(mediaQuery).toSet(),
              textDirection: textDirection,
              anchorRect: position.anchorRect,
              alignmentOffset: Offset.zero,
              menuPosition: position.position,
              menuAlignment: AlignmentDirectional.topStart,
              alignment: AlignmentDirectional.bottomStart,
            ),
            child: panel,
          );
        },
      ),
    );
  },
);

class _MenuLayout extends SingleChildLayoutDelegate {
  const _MenuLayout({
    required this.alignmentOffset,
    required this.anchorRect,
    required this.screenPadding,
    required this.avoidBounds,
    required this.alignment,
    required this.menuAlignment,
    required this.textDirection,
    required EdgeInsetsGeometry? padding,
    this.menuPosition,
  }) : menuPadding = padding;

  final ui.Rect anchorRect;
  final ui.Offset alignmentOffset;
  final ui.Offset? menuPosition;
  final EdgeInsets screenPadding;
  final EdgeInsetsGeometry? menuPadding;
  final Set<Rect> avoidBounds;
  final AlignmentGeometry alignment;
  final AlignmentGeometry menuAlignment;
  final ui.TextDirection textDirection;

  Rect _findClosestScreen(Size parentSize, Offset point, Set<Rect> avoidBounds) {
    final Iterable<ui.Rect> screens = DisplayFeatureSubScreen.subScreensInBounds(
      Offset.zero & parentSize,
      avoidBounds,
    );

    Rect closest = screens.first;
    for (final ui.Rect screen in screens.skip(1)) {
      if ((screen.center - point).distanceSquared < (closest.center - point).distanceSquared) {
        closest = screen;
      }
    }

    return closest;
  }

  Offset _fitInsideScreen(
    Rect screen,
    Size childSize,
    Offset position,
    Offset anchorPosition,
  ) {
    final EdgeInsets? padding = menuPadding?.resolve(textDirection);
    final Rect anchor = menuPosition == null ? anchorRect : anchorPosition & Size.zero;

    double x = position.dx;
    double y = position.dy;

    bool overLeftEdge(double x) => x < screen.left;
    bool overRightEdge(double x) => x > screen.right - childSize.width;
    bool overTopEdge(double y) => y < screen.top;
    bool overBottomEdge(double y) => y > screen.bottom - childSize.height;

    bool hasHorizontalAnchorOverlap = childSize.width >= screen.width;
    if (hasHorizontalAnchorOverlap) {
      x = screen.left;
    } else {
      double? shiftX;
      if (padding != null && padding.horizontal > 0) {
        double ratio = (x - anchorPosition.dx) / childSize.width;
        ratio = ui.clampDouble(ratio, -1, 0);
        shiftX = padding.right * ratio + padding.left * (ratio + 1);
        x -= shiftX;
      }

      if (overLeftEdge(x)) {
        double flipX = anchor.center.dx * 2 - position.dx - childSize.width;
        if (shiftX != null) {
          flipX -= padding!.horizontal + shiftX;
        }

        hasHorizontalAnchorOverlap = overRightEdge(flipX);
        if (hasHorizontalAnchorOverlap || overLeftEdge(flipX)) {
          x = screen.left;
        } else {
          x = flipX;
        }
      } else if (overRightEdge(x)) {
        double flipX = anchor.center.dx * 2 - position.dx - childSize.width;
        if (shiftX != null) {
          flipX += padding!.horizontal - shiftX;
        }

        hasHorizontalAnchorOverlap = overLeftEdge(flipX);
        if (hasHorizontalAnchorOverlap || overRightEdge(flipX)) {
          x = screen.right - childSize.width;
        } else {
          x = flipX;
        }
      }
    }

    if (childSize.height >= screen.height) {
      return Offset(x, screen.top);
    }

    if (hasHorizontalAnchorOverlap && !anchor.isEmpty) {
      final double below = anchor.bottom - y;
      final double above = y + childSize.height - anchor.top;
      if (below > 0 && above > 0) {
        if (below > above) {
          y = anchor.top - childSize.height;
        } else {
          y = anchor.bottom;
        }
      }
    }

    double? shiftY;
    if (padding != null && padding.vertical > 0) {
      double ratio = (y - anchorPosition.dy) / childSize.height;
      ratio = ui.clampDouble(ratio, -1, 0);
      shiftY = padding.bottom * ratio + padding.top * (ratio + 1);
      y -= shiftY;
    }

    if (overTopEdge(y)) {
      double flipY = anchor.center.dy * 2 - position.dy - childSize.height;
      if (shiftY != null) {
        flipY -= padding!.vertical + shiftY;
      }

      if (overTopEdge(flipY) || overBottomEdge(flipY)) {
        y = screen.top;
      } else {
        y = flipY;
      }
    } else if (overBottomEdge(y)) {
      double flipY = anchor.center.dy * 2 - position.dy - childSize.height;
      if (shiftY != null) {
        flipY += padding!.vertical - shiftY;
      }

      if (overTopEdge(flipY) || overBottomEdge(flipY)) {
        y = screen.bottom - childSize.height;
      } else {
        y = flipY;
      }
    }

    return Offset(x, y);
  }

  @override
  BoxConstraints getConstraintsForChild(BoxConstraints constraints) {
    return BoxConstraints.loose(constraints.biggest).deflate(screenPadding);
  }

  @override
  Offset getPositionForChild(Size size, Size childSize) {
    Offset anchorOffset;
    if (menuPosition == null) {
      anchorOffset = alignment.resolve(textDirection).withinRect(anchorRect);
      anchorOffset += switch (textDirection) {
        ui.TextDirection.ltr => alignmentOffset,
        ui.TextDirection.rtl => alignment is AlignmentDirectional
            ? Offset(-alignmentOffset.dx, alignmentOffset.dy)
            : alignmentOffset,
      };
    } else {
      anchorOffset = anchorRect.topLeft + menuPosition!;
    }

    final ui.Offset position =
        anchorOffset - menuAlignment.resolve(textDirection).alongSize(childSize);

    final Rect screen = _findClosestScreen(
      size,
      anchorRect.center,
      avoidBounds,
    );

    return _fitInsideScreen(
      screenPadding.deflateRect(screen),
      childSize,
      position,
      anchorOffset,
    );
  }

  @override
  bool shouldRelayout(_MenuLayout oldDelegate) {
    return anchorRect != oldDelegate.anchorRect ||
        alignment != oldDelegate.alignment ||
        alignmentOffset != oldDelegate.alignmentOffset ||
        menuAlignment != oldDelegate.menuAlignment ||
        menuPosition != oldDelegate.menuPosition ||
        menuPadding != oldDelegate.menuPadding ||
        screenPadding != oldDelegate.screenPadding ||
        textDirection != oldDelegate.textDirection ||
        !setEquals(avoidBounds, oldDelegate.avoidBounds);
  }
}
```

</details>

So, the reason why a default constructor exists is because its overkill for most users. Similar to how users use Widgets instead of RenderObjects, except in rare cases. 
  - The MenuAnchor() is out-of-the-box.
  - RawMenuAnchor() is white label.
  - RawMenuAnchor.overlayBuilder() is fully custom.

> Not being able to use RawMenuOverlay or RawMenuSemantics is expectable, since these basic widgets are meant for replacement in more complicated designs. As I said I'm mostly trying to understand the capability of the default constructor. I noticed that the material menu anchor has to use `.overlayBuilder` as well (it might be helpful if you can illustrate the reason.)
> 
> Is it correct to think that the default constructor is adequate for basic menus, but is not sufficient for more established design languages?

<details><summary>Response</summary>
Elaborate on established design systems? The default constructor doesn't define any appearance, only positioning and behavior, and behavior can be modified by adding a shortcuts widget around the panel. The RawMenuPanel is what is giving the examples an appearance, but it's optional and I wouldn't mind removing it completely.

For the MenuAnchor, we actually could use the default constructor. There are a few things preventing me from doing so on this commit:
1. The commit is already huge, and I didn't want to add more changes.
2. The RawMenuAnchor used to take a list of children instead of a panel.
4. The MenuAnchor has a placement "bug" (it doesn't actually degrade function, but submenus can appear slightly misaligned when applying padding) because overflow flip handling doesn't account for padding or alignment.
    - RawMenuAnchor handles padding by flipping over the anchor midpoint, which solves the problem for any conventional layout I've come across (https://menu-anchor.web.app/#/padding).
    - This would require changing tests 

Honestly, it's mostly because this commit is so big. In fact, we could land the overlayBuilder then add the RawMenuPanel in later on, if that'd be simpler. Most tests use the default constructor because it basically just redirects to the overlayBuilder, but I could create a default constructor that only exists in RawMenuAnchorTest.dart.

There are also features that should probably be added to MenuAnchor from RawMenuAnchor to make it more more accessible/customizable, but I would need to add additional tests:
- There is no way to align a menu based on a point relative to the menu surface, which RawMenuAnchor implements (menuAlignment).
- Home/End don't focus the first/last menu items
- Down/Up don't consistently focus the first/last menu items
- There is no way to provide a semantic label around the menu's overlay
- I _think_ MenuAnchor/Submenu could be merged into a single widget, but this is something that I need to investigate further.
- MenuAnchor uses an optional CompositedTransformFollower? I think there's a plan to remove it due to a few bugs it caused. 

When using the OverlayBuilder, you have to manage all focus handling, so up/down do not always focus the first/last menu item when focusing from the anchor. Also, I just realized users would have to provide a flag regarding whether they want to handle their own focus, or have it be managed by the menu, even when providing a RawMenuSemantics widget. MenuAnchor already defined its own FocusScope, positioning, and tap region, so I left things as they were. That's also why there's duplicated logic between the two -- I don't want to mess with anything that can't be cleanly reverted.

</details>

> If so, I'd like to insist that the first priority of `RawMenuAnchor` should not to be directly used for building the basic menus, but to serve as building blocks of theme libraries. App developers (not library developers) should be unlikely to use `RawMenuAnchor` directly, but use themed widgets such as material menu anchor or the iOS drop down menus, which should indeed provide a simple basic version.


<details><summary>Response</summary>

From what I've observed, developers (and companies) explicitly ask for white label components to make it easier to implement their own design language. Some that I can think of:
- React-aria (https://react-spectrum.adobe.com/react-aria/Menu.html#menu-1)
- Angular CDK (https://material.angular.io/cdk/menu/examples#cdk-menu-menubar)
- Lion (https://lion.js.org/components/select-rich/overview/)
- Polymer Iron Components (https://www.webcomponents.org/element/@polymer/iron-dropdown/demo/demo/index.html)
- Base UI (https://mui.com/base-ui/react-menu/)
- Qt (https://doc.qt.io/qt-6/qtquickcontrols-menus.html)

I intend for users to use the default constructor as a fully-featured, accessible base whose appearance can be fully customized by providing a custom panel. The RawMenuPanel widget itself (the panel widget used in examples) probably doesn't need to exist, but it provides an easy template that users can copy. It could be removed though.

> Still I think there can be a better balance between them. Do you think keeping the `defaultOverlayBuilder` public (possibly with even more customization options) will help with the LOC for a basic menu? Can you evaluate it?
> 
Elaborate on this a bit. Right now, defaultOverlayBuilder is the default constructor's overlay builder, similar to AnimatedSwitcher.defaultTransitionBuilder, except that it can't be static since it relies on instance properties (i.e. the panel). It's basically a way of creating a redirecting constructor without losing parameter documentation. But I'm not sure how we could customize the defaultOverlayBuilder?

</details>

Edit: 

Here is the RawMenuAnchor overlay compared to the MenuAnchor overlay. I removed the menu style resolution because styles can be resolved above or below the RawMenuAnchor() widget. The only material-specific bit is the padding offset, which makes sure submenus align with their parents. This can be resolved in _MenuAnchorState and passed to RawMenuAnchor, which handles the offset). I'm pretty sure it can be completely replaced with the default constructor.

<details><summary>RawMenuAnchor overlay</summary>

```dart
class _MenuOverlay extends StatelessWidget {
  const _MenuOverlay({
    required this.alignmentOffset,
    required this.alignment,
    required this.menuAlignment,
    required this.position,
    required this.padding,
    this.semanticLabel,
    this.consumeOutsideTaps = true,
    required this.child,
  });

  final Offset alignmentOffset;
  final RawMenuAnchorOverlayPosition position;
  final Widget child;
  final EdgeInsetsGeometry? padding;
  final bool consumeOutsideTaps;
  final AlignmentGeometry? alignment;
  final AlignmentGeometry? menuAlignment;
  final String? semanticLabel;

  static final Map<Type, Action<Intent>> _defaultOverlayActions = <Type, Action<Intent>>{
    DirectionalFocusIntent: _OverlayDirectionalFocusAction(), // Focus nested menus
    _FocusFirstMenuItemIntent: _FocusFirstMenuItemAction(),   // Focus first on home
    _FocusLastMenuItemIntent: _FocusLastMenuItemAction(),     // Focus last on end
  };

  @override
  Widget build(BuildContext context) {
    final MenuController menuController = MenuController.maybeOf(context)!;
    final _RawMenuAnchorOverlayState anchor = menuController._anchor! as _RawMenuAnchorOverlayState;

    final Widget panel = Semantics.fromProperties(
      explicitChildNodes: true,
      properties: SemanticsProperties(
        scopesRoute: true,
        label: semanticLabel,
      ),
      // Mouse region is deliberately not included here because users can add it
      // to their panel if they want to change the cursor.
      child: TapRegion(
        groupId: position.tapRegionGroupId,
        consumeOutsideTaps: consumeOutsideTaps,
        onTapOutside: (PointerDownEvent event) {
          menuController.close();
        },
        child: FocusScope(
          node: anchor._menuScopeNode,
          skipTraversal: true,
          descendantsAreFocusable: true,
          child: Actions(
            actions: _defaultOverlayActions,
            child: Shortcuts(
              shortcuts: <ShortcutActivator, Intent>{
                SingleActivator(LogicalKeyboardKey.gameButtonA): ActivateIntent(),
                SingleActivator(LogicalKeyboardKey.escape): DismissIntent(),
                SingleActivator(LogicalKeyboardKey.tab): NextFocusIntent(),
                SingleActivator(LogicalKeyboardKey.tab, shift: true): PreviousFocusIntent(),
                SingleActivator(LogicalKeyboardKey.arrowDown):
                    DirectionalFocusIntent(TraversalDirection.down),
                SingleActivator(LogicalKeyboardKey.arrowUp):
                    DirectionalFocusIntent(TraversalDirection.up),
                // No left/right handling, but this can be added by children.
              },
              child: child,
            ),
          ),
        ),
      ),
    );

    return ConstrainedBox(
      constraints: BoxConstraints.loose(position.overlaySize),
      child: Builder(
        builder: (BuildContext context) {
          final MediaQueryData mediaQuery = MediaQuery.of(context);
          final TextDirection textDirection = Directionality.of(context);
          // Resolve fallback alignment here so that alignmentOffset defaults to
          // being directionally-agnostic.
          final AlignmentGeometry anchorAlignment = alignment ??
              (anchor._isRootAnchor
                      ? AlignmentDirectional.bottomStart
                      : AlignmentDirectional.topEnd)
                  .resolve(textDirection);
          return CustomSingleChildLayout(
            delegate: _MenuLayout(
              screenPadding: mediaQuery.padding,
              padding: padding,
              avoidBounds: DisplayFeatureSubScreen.avoidBounds(mediaQuery).toSet(),
              textDirection: textDirection,
              anchorRect: position.anchorRect,
              alignmentOffset: alignmentOffset,
              menuPosition: position.position,
              menuAlignment: menuAlignment ?? AlignmentDirectional.topStart,
              alignment: anchorAlignment,
            ),
            child: panel,
          );
        },
      ),
    );
  }
}
```

</details>


<details><summary>MenuAnchor</summary> 

```dart
class _Submenu extends StatelessWidget {
  const _Submenu({
    required this.anchor,
    required this.layerLink,
    required this.menuStyle,
    required this.menuPosition,
    required this.alignmentOffset,
    required this.consumeOutsideTaps,
    required this.clipBehavior,
    this.crossAxisUnconstrained = true,
    required this.menuChildren,
    required this.menuScopeNode,
  });

  final FocusScopeNode menuScopeNode;
  final RawMenuAnchorOverlayPosition menuPosition;
  final _MenuAnchorState anchor;
  final MouseCursor mouseCursor;
  final LayerLink? layerLink;
  final bool consumeOutsideTaps;
  final Offset alignmentOffset;
  final Clip clipBehavior;
  final bool crossAxisUnconstrained;
  final List<Widget> menuChildren;

  @override
  Widget build(BuildContext context) {
    final Widget menuPanel = TapRegion(
      groupId: menuPosition.tapRegionGroupId,
      // Not sure why _menuController.isOpen is being checked, because the tap
      // region shouldn't be active if it's been unmounted.
      consumeOutsideTaps: anchor._root._menuController.isOpen && anchor.widget.consumeOutsideTap,
      onTapOutside: (PointerDownEvent event) {
        anchor._menuController.close();
      },
      child: MouseRegion(
        cursor: mouseCursor,
        hitTestBehavior: HitTestBehavior.deferToChild,
        child: FocusScope(
          node: anchor._menuScopeNode,
          skipTraversal: true,
          child: Actions(
            actions: <Type, Action<Intent>>{
              DismissIntent: DismissMenuAction(controller: anchor._menuController),
            },
            child: Shortcuts(
              shortcuts: <ShortcutActivator, Intent>{
                SingleActivator(LogicalKeyboardKey.gameButtonA): ActivateIntent(),
                SingleActivator(LogicalKeyboardKey.escape): DismissIntent(),
                SingleActivator(LogicalKeyboardKey.tab): NextFocusIntent(),
                SingleActivator(LogicalKeyboardKey.tab, shift: true): PreviousFocusIntent(),
                SingleActivator(LogicalKeyboardKey.arrowDown):
                    DirectionalFocusIntent(TraversalDirection.down),
                SingleActivator(LogicalKeyboardKey.arrowUp):
                    DirectionalFocusIntent(TraversalDirection.up),
                SingleActivator(LogicalKeyboardKey.arrowLeft):
                    DirectionalFocusIntent(TraversalDirection.left),
                SingleActivator(LogicalKeyboardKey.arrowRight):
                    DirectionalFocusIntent(TraversalDirection.right),
              },
              child: child,
            ),
          ),
        ),
      ),
    );

    // I think the theme should be applied to the menu panel, not the overlay,
    // but I'm leaving it here just in case.
    final Widget layout = Theme(
      data: Theme.of(context).copyWith(visualDensity: visualDensity),
      child: ConstrainedBox(
        constraints: BoxConstraints.loose(menuPosition.overlaySize),
        child: Builder(builder: (BuildContext context) {
          final MediaQueryData mediaQuery = MediaQuery.of(context);
          return CustomSingleChildLayout(
            delegate: _MenuLayout(
              anchorRect: menuPosition.anchorRect,
              textDirection: Directionality.of(context),
              avoidBounds: DisplayFeatureSubScreen.avoidBounds(mediaQuery).toSet(),
              menuPadding: resolvedPadding,
              alignment: alignment,
              alignmentOffset: alignmentOffset,
              menuPosition: menuPosition.position,
              orientation:
                  anchor._orientation, // Unnecessary because of RawMenuAnchor layout handling.
              parentOrientation: anchor._parent?._orientation ??
                  Axis.horizontal, // Unnecessary because of RawMenuAnchor layout handling.
            ),
            child: menuPanel,
          );
        }),
      ),
    );

    if (layerLink == null) {
      return layout;
    }
    // I believe this is going to be removed.
    return CompositedTransformFollower(
      link: layerLink!,
      targetAnchor: Alignment.bottomLeft,
      child: layout,
    );
  }
}
```
</details>
